Before populating "Actions" I am checking whether a drive is resettable.
Wow, sorry I missed this.  Generally ou would rely on the interface existing on the device to know if it's resettable (non resettable drives won't have a reset interface)

oh, so instead of https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/blob/master/yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/Inventory/Item/Drive.interface.yaml, it should have like `xyz.openbmc_project.Inventory.Item.ResettableDrive` or something similar to indicate that this is resetable?

This isn't the interface name you searched for on line 638.  There is no guarantee that a drive supports the transition interface, especially when you didn't search for it explicitly in the mapper.  In theory, it could also be hosted by another object.

https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/blob/master/yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/State/Drive.interface.yaml

The Transition is the `State.Drive` and the `State.Drive.Transition` is one of the property for RequestedDriveTransition.

The actions supported is checked in `requestDriveResetAction`.

Please take a look at the updated code.
 
This is searching for subtrees under /xyz/openbmc_project/inventory that implements
xyz.openbmc_project.State.Drive interface. So as I understand, if a drive doesn't implement xyz.openbmc_project.State.Drive interface this will fail with resourceNotFound.
Yep, but what if you have a drive that doesn't support the State.Drive or State.Drive.Transition interfaces?  Or hosts them from a different interface compared to the drive inventory item?

um, I forgot if `GetSubTree`'s interfaces mean that it returns if it matches at least one or all of them. I think it should be if it match one, right?

(I probably need to test it bit more to see if I missed anything else.).
Please don't capture/copy request like this.  Read the json values in in the first scope and pass only the values you need down.  This will break in the future when the $expand parameter is added.

Drives that don't support reset aren't an internal error. most drives won't be directly resettable.

Also, if no drives exist in the system this will give 500 instead of 404.  Please test that and improve this error handling.
My thinking is that only drive that exist will get expose this URI. Maybe that is not correct. Let me take a closer look.

Please take a look at the updated code.

/redfish/v1/Systems/system/Storage/1/Drives/{}/Actions/Drive.Reset will not show up on Drive unless the drive is resettable.

If no drive is present,

```
wget --some_flags http://{port}/redfish/v1/Systems/system/Storage/1/Drives/{aDriveName}
```

will return

```
wget: server returned error: HTTP/1.1 404 Not Found
```

The ResetType is optional, should use the default reset if the string is empty.


Probably Powercycle.

Please answer "why" in your commit message.
Yes, we need to know why we need this and what benefit it has. To this change, we can reference Google's use case
I have added the why in the message. I just mentioned that we needed out of band reset to update the drive firmware.
Are we sure we want power cycle here?  I thought we did a different reset type by default in chassis?

it seems like Chassis Reset doesn't support optional ResetType, since that support in bmcweb is added after its implementation.

https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/2b82937ecef572954b49569177b16831cbc09cfe/redfish-core/lib/chassis.hpp#L645-L673
What's the difference between these in a drive context?

From my understanding with the drive that we are testing with (not 100% sure if that common across everything), 

- Powercycle: Powercycle the whole PCIe card/Drive + Storage Controller.
- ForceRestart: In our context, it is being used as reset  and just reboot the Drive itself.
Is this explained in the spec somewhere?

Do you mean Drive or just ResetType in general? I don't have the spec in the Drive context.

https://www.dmtf.org/sites/default/files/standards/documents/DSP2046_2022.1.pdf#page=100

snippet from the schema,
```
ForceRestart: Shut down immediately and non-gracefully and restart the system.
PowerCycle: Power cycle the unit. Behaves like a full power removal, followed by a power restore to the resource.
```
Please don't use brace initialization for these.  This is a new requirement since the original patch was submitted, but I'd like to not regress.
Done
